Author: designer#4893
Content:
I'm the one who thinks China's economy and society are going to have a big crack. 
than when a social rift leads to an economic rift, economic cracks more often lead to social cracks. 
the problem is the timing, perhaps five years later, when look back at the world, I think people will nod and understand.

If about 150 of the 1000 global enterprises are Chinese enterprises, half of them are state-owned enterprises. 
I think half of them should already have been bankrupt. 
this distorted market structure and the existence of authoritarian dictatorship is a serious threat to us.

I think that the maximum amount that civilization can reach is in places where freedom coexists with order. usually, emphasis of order restrains freedom, and granting of liberty leads to disorder. United States has a lot of energy of free and Japan has a lot of energy of order. there is a fear of freedom and disorder in China.

Author: designer#4893
Content:
economic crises over the last 30years have revealed that the rapid growth of the economy, which is not supported by the level of consciousness and democracy in the economic development stage, ends with hard-landing. we are just waiting for time to confirm the principle again in China. (there are hopes for young people in China, but it will take a very long time.)

If the linked Xinhua report is correct, it is highly likely that the regulation that limited the term of Chinese President and his successor to a consecutive term will disappear. I think China will open up Xi Jinping's long-term rule and enter the hard-landing path at the same time. http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-02/25/c_136998770.htm

expect to experience hard landing by the end of 2019. It will be Japanese economy that sees the most profit in this situation.
